The nation is stunned as President Johnson abruptly removes several key members of Lincoln’s wartime Cabinet. Newspapers buzz with accusations of political vendetta and fears that Reconstruction policy will be gutted. On Capitol Hill, tempers flare as legislators debate how far a president’s power to fire his own appointees should go.

@Tenure

Radical Republicans in Congress, joined by many moderates, argue that Johnson’s sudden Cabinet purge proves the need for new legal restraints on presidential power. They push for the **Tenure of Office Act**, a law that would require Senate approval before the president can remove officials confirmed by that same Senate. Conservatives call it an unconstitutional overreach, while radicals see it as essential to protecting Reconstruction from sabotage.

